HDF5—Hierarchical Data Format—is a binary data format designed to store and organize large amounts of data. It allows:

  • convenient access to the stored data from programming languages such as Python and Matlab,
  • annotation and hierarchical structuring of the data, and
  • efficient storage of the data.

The fact that the data can be structured and annotated, allows for helpful self-documentation, i.a., one file holds both the data and its description. This goes far beyond, e.g., what is reasonable to put in the headers of a spreadsheet.

Efficient storage makes it possible to store and transfer larger amounts of data than is possible with other formats, such as CSV or Excel. The storage gains are of the order of a factor 10 when comparing to, e.g., uncompressed CSV and a factor 2 when comparing to compressed CSV. The storage efficiency is due to the use of transparent compression and binary data formats (e.g., float and int types) rather than as text.

This tutorial will show how to use Python and Matlab to read and explore the data in an HDF5-files. (In case you are interested in writing HDF5 files, first work through this tutorial and then consult the documentation of the HDF5 tools used here. I would also be glad to exchange experiences.) We take a file with meteorological from the off-shore met mast at the OWEZ off-shore wind farm as our working example. Feedback to improve the tutorial is welcome.

Some more information:

  • HDF5 website
  • HDF5 on Wikipedia
  • OWEZ website

Python

Required Software

Next to Python, we will be using the standard library package datetime and the external packages h5py, numpy, and matplotlib. So make sure to install these if they aren't already. We will be using Python 3.4, but any version including 2.7 should work.

This tutorial will be console-based. You can use the standard Python console, IPython, or some Python IDE, e.g., Spyder. I assume that you are familiar with working with a Python console.

Preparing the Stage

First, we need to import the packages we are going to use:

>>> import numpy as np
>>> import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
>>> import datetime as dt
>>> import h5py

Of this set of packages, only h5py is really required to explore HDF5 files, but the others are useful for playing with the data therein.

More information:

  • h5py documentation

A First Look

Now, let us open the HDF5 file and have a first look at what is inside:

>>> f = h5py.File('OWEZ.h5')

>>> dict(f)
{'channel': <HDF5 group "/channel" (48 members)>,
 'coordinates': <HDF5 group "/coordinates" (3 members)>,
 'device': <HDF5 group "/device" (9 members)>,
 'time': <HDF5 group "/time" (6 members)>}

Here, I am assuming that your present working directory (pwd) contains the HDF5 file OWEZ.h5. We see that the file object f provides a dict-like interface to its contents. These contents can be groups or datasets, ordered in a hierarchical structure comparable to a file system. In the file system analogy, groups correspond to directories and datasets correspond to files. (There also exist hard and soft links, but that would lead too far for this tutorial)

Every element of the hierarchical structure can be annotated with attribute–value pairs, which are accessed via the dict-like attrs attribute:

>>> list(f.attrs.keys())
['description',
 'source',
 'author',
 'annotations',
 'data_processing',
 'HDF5-conversion',
 'references']

>>> print(repr(f.attrs['description'][:60] + '…'))
'This file mainly contains the datasets of the met mast at th…'

Oops! That was a long list. These are the 58 data ‘channels’, the structuring of the datasets in the original Excel files. We can access these subgroups in two ways, dict-style or filesystem-style:

>>> f['channel']['00']
<HDF5 group "/channel/00" (4 members)>

>>> f['channel/05']
<HDF5 group "/channel/05" (4 members)>

Let us go further down the hierarchy still and see what's inside one of these channels:

>>> c13 = f['channel/13']

>>> dict(c13.attrs)
{'channel': '13', 'device': 'CA', 'location': 'NE70', 'quantity': 'ws'}

>>> dict(c13)
{'Max': <HDF5 dataset "Max": shape (289296,), type "<f2">,
 'Mean': <HDF5 dataset "Mean": shape (289296,), type "<f4">,
 'Min': <HDF5 dataset "Min": shape (289296,), type "<f2">,
 'StdDev': <HDF5 dataset "StdDev": shape (289296,), type "<f2">}

The group attributes tersely tell us this channel contains wind speed data from a cup anemometer from the North-East end of the tower at 70 meters height. We see that this group contains some datasets. Each contains 289296 data points in a linear array. All data points in each dataset have the same type. These datasets of channel 13 contain 2 or 4-byte floating point numbers.

Toying with Datasets

Let us have a look at these datasets (click pictures to unscale/rescale them):

>>> c13['Mean'].value
array([  3.44060493,   3.26941991,   3.32937908, ...,   8.77543259,
         9.77739906,  10.2571497 ], dtype=float32)

>>> c13Min, c13Max, c13Mean, c13StdDev = \
... c13['Min'].value, c13['Max'].value, c13['Mean'].value, c13['StdDev'].value

>>> plt.plot(c13Mean + c13StdDev, 'g'), plt.plot(c13Mean - c13StdDev, 'g'), \
... plt.plot(c13Min, 'r'), plt.plot(c13Max, 'r'), \
... plt.plot(c13Mean, 'b');

We see that the values are what is to be expected of wind speed measurements. There are, however, some gaps. These are due to missing data, which is encoded as float ‘NaN’ (Not-a-Number) values. What's the percentage of these in the dataset? Do we need to worry about those when analyzing the data? (Yes!)

>>> np.round(np.mean(np.isnan(c13Mean)) * 100)
8.0 # The 0 after the decimal sign gives the wrong impression
    # that it is rounded to one decimal place; it isn't,
    # it is rounded to the nearest integer

>>> np.mean(c13Mean)
nan

>>> np.nanmean(c13Mean)
8.1629915

>>> np.nanmin(c13Mean), np.nanmax(c13Mean)
(0.0, 29.725368)

Furthermore, the plot we showed is not all that legible; let us make a more interesting one by zooming in on the first day of—10-minute—data:

>>> s = slice(6*24)
>>> plt.plot(c13Mean[s] + c13StdDev[s], 'g'), plt.plot(c13Mean[s] - c13StdDev[s], 'g'), \
... plt.plot(c13Min[s], 'r'), plt.plot(c13Max[s], 'r'), \
... plt.plot(c13Mean[s], 'b');

Datasets can also have attributes, but that is not being used in the OWEZ HDF5 file we are using here. One use case for that would be to store data that is removed for some reason from the dataset. In our file, this has been done at the group (channel) level. We first look at which channels have which attributes and then have a look at an ‘interesting’ one:

>>> key2channel = dict()
... for channel, group in f['channel'].items():
...    for key in group.attrs.keys():
...        if key not in key2channel:
...            key2channel[key] = {channel}
...        else:
...            key2channel[key].add(channel)
... for key, channels in key2channel.items():
...    print(repr(key) + ':', channels)
...

Next to the description, which describes why the values were removed, and the removed values themselves, also—obviously—timestamps of the removed data points are listed, so that we can reconstruct the original datasets, if needed.

Exploring the Hierarchy

Now that we know what groups and datasets are, we can explore the structure of the HDF5 file a bit more, to learn how it can be used to store the datasets in a self-describing way.

As a reminder, let us recall the highest level of the file:

>>> dict(f)
{'channel': <HDF5 group "/channel" (48 members)>,
 'coordinates': <HDF5 group "/coordinates" (3 members)>,
 'device': <HDF5 group "/device" (9 members)>,
 'time': <HDF5 group "/time" (6 members)>}

We have looked at the 'channel' group, which structured the datasets according to the scheme used in the original Excel data files.

Time

From the original files however, the time instant columns were ‘moved’:

>>> dict(f['time'])
{'day': <HDF5 dataset "day": shape (289296,), type "|i1">,
 'hour': <HDF5 dataset "hour": shape (289296,), type "|i1">,
 'minute': <HDF5 dataset "minute": shape (289296,), type "|i1">,
 'month': <HDF5 dataset "month": shape (289296,), type "|i1">,
 'timestamp': <HDF5 dataset "timestamp": shape (289296,), type "<i4">,
 'year': <HDF5 dataset "year": shape (289296,), type "<i2">}

>>> f['time/timestamp'].attrs['description']
'The time instances encoded in unix time, the number of seconds that have elapsed since 1970-01-01T00:00:00 (UTC).'
>>> f['time/timestamp'].value
array([1120176000, 1120176600, 1120177200, ..., 1293838200, 1293838800,
       1293839400], dtype=int32)
>>> t = f['time/timestamp'].value

>>> f['time/year'].value
array([2005, 2005, 2005, ..., 2011, 2011, 2011], dtype=int16)
>>> y = f['time/year'].value

>>> f['time/month'].value
array([7, 7, 7, ..., 1, 1, 1], dtype=int8)
>>> m = f['time/month'].value

We have saved the timestamp, year and month values for convenient indexing.

Device–Quantity–Location Hierarchy

The datasets are also available in an alternative structure from the channel one. Namely, they can be accessed through the device–quantity–location hierarchy:

>>> f['device'].attrs['description'][:72] + '…'
'This group contains a device/quantity/location ordering of the datasets.…'
>>> d = f['device']
>>> dict(d)
{'AC': <HDF5 group "/device/AC" (2 members)>,
 'AWAC': <HDF5 group "/device/AWAC" (9 members)>,
 'CA': <HDF5 group "/device/CA" (1 members)>,
 'HMP': <HDF5 group "/device/HMP" (2 members)>,
 'PD': <HDF5 group "/device/PD" (1 members)>,
 'RPT': <HDF5 group "/device/RPT" (1 members)>,
 'ST': <HDF5 group "/device/ST" (1 members)>,
 'WM': <HDF5 group "/device/WM" (3 members)>,
 'WV': <HDF5 group "/device/WV" (1 members)>}

>>> dict(d['HMP'])
{'at': <HDF5 group "/device/HMP/at" (3 members)>,
 'rh': <HDF5 group "/device/HMP/rh" (3 members)>}
>>> set(d['HMP'].attrs.keys())
{'description', 'make', 'note', 'owez_code', 'reference', 'type'}
>>> d['HMP'].attrs['description']
'relative humidity and ambient temperature sensors'

>>> at = d['HMP/at']
>>> set(at.attrs.keys())
Out[36]:
{'accuracy',
 'description',
 'error_propagation',
 'range',
 'sampling_frequency',
 'storage',
 'temperature_dependence',
 'unit'}
>>> at.attrs['description'], at.attrs['unit'], at.attrs['range'], at.attrs['accuracy']
('ambient temperature', '°C', '-40°C..+80°C', '0.1°C (at 20°C)')
>>> dict(at)
{'S116': <HDF5 group "/device/HMP/at/S116" (4 members)>,
 'S21': <HDF5 group "/device/HMP/at/S21" (4 members)>,
 'S70': <HDF5 group "/device/HMP/at/S70" (4 members)>}

>>> dict(at['S70'].attrs)
{'channel': '19', 'device': 'HMP', 'location': 'S70', 'quantity': 'at'}
>>> at.get('S70', getlink=True)
<SoftLink to "/channel/19">

So we see that in this alternative hierarchy, the datasets can be reached by specifying the device, quantity, and location, in that order. At that point, we find again the same datasets we encountered in the flat channel hierarchy. These have been grafted here using so-called ‘soft’ links (this does not matter much in practice).

What is especially convenient about such a more descriptive hierarchy is that at the right level metadata of interest can be added. For example references to device make and data sheets:

>>> d['HMP'].attrs['make']
'Vaisala Oyj'
>>> d['HMP'].attrs['reference'][:72] + '…'
"HMP230 Series Transmitters User's Guide (2002-05) from Vaisala Oyj <http…"

Given that it is natural that each quantity is treated in the same way, information about the data processing is stored at that level:

>>> at.attrs['sampling_frequency']
'unknown (assumed to be smaller than 3495 Hz)'
>>> at.attrs['error_propagation']
'Given that √(3495*600) is about 1500, a lower bound of the accuracy of Mean values is 0.1°C/1500 = ⅔·10¯⁴°C.'
>>> at.attrs['storage'][:72] + '…'
'The Max and Min values are stored as float16 values, which results in a …'

(As you see, attributes can store anything, even information that shows an embarrassing lack of knowledge!)

Toying with Datasets Again

Plotting against the timestamps is straightforward:

>>> at70Min, at70Max, at70Mean, at70StdDev = \
... at70['Min'].value, at70['Max'].value, at70['Mean'].value, at70['StdDev'].value

>>> plt.plot(t, at70Mean + at70StdDev, 'g'), plt.plot(t, at70Mean - at70StdDev, 'g'), \
... plt.plot(t, at70Min, 'r'), plt.plot(t, at70Max, 'r'), \
... plt.plot(t, at70Mean, 'b');

The seasonal variation in temperature is clearly apparent and should be expected.

Zooming in on a specific part—e.g., the summer of 2009—of the dataset is simplified by using the year and month indexes we encountered earlier:

>>> s = (y == 2009) & (m > 6) & (m < 9)
>>> plt.plot(t[s], at70Mean[s] + at70StdDev[s], 'g'), plt.plot(t[s], at70Mean[s] - at70StdDev[s], 'g'), \
... plt.plot(t[s], at70Min[s], 'r'), plt.plot(t[s], at70Max[s], 'r'), \
... plt.plot(t[s], at70Mean[s], 'b');

Now the diurnal variation starts to become apparent.

The highest temperature seems to have occurred in the second half of August, but let's find this out more precisely.

>>> np.nanmax(at70Max[s])
27.609

>>> i = np.argmax(at70Max[s])
>>> at70Max[s][i]
nan

>>> b = ~np.isnan(at70Max[s])
>>> i = np.argmax(at70Max[s][b])
>>> at70Max[s][b][i]
27.609

>>> t[s][b][i]
1250767200
>>> dt.datetime.fromtimestamp(t[s][b][i]).isoformat()
'2009-08-20T13:20:00'

>>> a = f['time/day'].value
>>> s = (y == 2009) & (m == 8) & (a == 20)
>>> b = ~np.isnan(at70Max[s])
>>> i = np.argmax(at70Max[s][b])
>>> h = (t[s] - t[s][b][i])/60/60 # we center the plot at the hottest time
>>> plt.plot(h, at70Mean[s] + at70StdDev[s], 'g'), plt.plot(h, at70Mean[s] - at70StdDev[s], 'g'), \
... plt.plot(h, at70Min[s], 'r'), plt.plot(h, at70Max[s], 'r'), \
... plt.plot(h, at70Mean[s], 'b');

Closing

If you managed to work through all of the above examples, you should be ready to independently work with HDF5 files yourself using the h5py package. Remember that the hierarchy of each HDF5 file can be different, so it will be necessary to acquaint yourself with it a bit before working with the data.

In case you are dealing with a HDF5 file that you want to augment or improve, or if you want to create an HDF5 file for some dataset, I advise you to go over the documentation for the h5py package. Typically, you will also need to use a package to import the data from a CSV or Excel file and create an initial HDF5 file you can start from. I have made good use of the Pandas library for that purpose. It has convenient input-output routines you can use. When you start modifying HDF5 files, then h5repack is also a necessary tool to clean up old cruft. Also, don't hesitate to contact me with questions; if I have time, I'll gladly help you along.

Success & have fun!

Matlab

For this Matlab-part of the tutorial, I will be using Matlab 2016b, but non-ancient older versions should work as well.

The latest version of Matlab's own .mat file format (7.3) is actually based on HDF5. However, for those files Matlab uses their own pre-defined structure, so this does not have any impact for us, expect perhaps for the fact that Matlab has extensive HDF5 capabilities built-in.

This tutorial will be console-based. Matlab help and documentation for its HDF5 functionality can be accessed by:

>> doc hdf5 % Summary of MATLAB hdf5 capabilities.
>> doc h5info % Return information about HDF5 file
>> doc h5disp % Display contents of HDF5 file
>> doc h5read % Read data from HDF5 data set
>> doc h5readatt % Read attribute from HDF5 file

Some more information:

  • Matlab example on HDF5 website

I would be very grateful for improvement feedback on this Matlab-part of the tutorial, especially on how to more compactly output struct (sub)fields.

A First Look

Now, let us have a first look at what is inside the HDF5 file:

>> info = h5info('OWEZ.h5')

ans =

  struct with fields:

      Filename: '/home/equaeghe/temp/OWEZ_M_181/OWEZ.27.h5'
          Name: '/'
        Groups: [4×1 struct]
      Datasets: []
     Datatypes: []
         Links: []
    Attributes: [7×1 struct]

>> {info.Groups.Name}

ans =

  1×4 cell array

    '/channel'    '/coordinates'    '/device'    '/time'

Here, I am assuming that your present working directory (pwd) contains the HDF5 file OWEZ.h5. We see that h5info provides a struct containing a description of the contents of the HDF5 file. These contents can be groups or datasets, ordered in a hierarchical structure comparable to a file system. In the file system analogy, groups correspond to directories and datasets correspond to files. (There also exist hard and soft links, but that would lead too far for this tutorial)

Every element of the hierarchical structure can be annotated with attribute–value pairs, which are discovered and accessed as follows:

>> {info.Attributes.Name}

ans =

  1×7 cell array

  Columns 1 through 4

    'description'    'source'    'author'    'annotations'

  Columns 5 through 7

    'data_processing'    'HDF5-conversion'    'references'

>> h5readatt('OWEZ.h5', '/', 'description')

ans =

  cell

    'This file mainly contains the datasets of the met mast at the Egmond aan Zee Offshore Wind Farm…'

Digging Deeper

Let us have a look at one of the groups:

>> info_channel = h5info('OWEZ.h5', '/channel')

info_channel =

  struct with fields:

      Filename: '/home/equaeghe/temp/OWEZ_M_181/OWEZ.27.h5'
          Name: '/channel'
        Groups: [48×1 struct]
      Datasets: []
     Datatypes: []
         Links: []
    Attributes: [1×1 struct]

>> {info_channel.Attributes.Name}

ans =

  cell

    'description'

>> info_channel.Attributes.Value

ans =

  cell

    'This group contains the channel-based ordering of the datasets as described in the data manual …'

>> {info_channel.Groups.Name}

  1×48 cell array

  Columns 1 through 6

    '/channel/00'    '/channel/01'    '/channel/02'    '/channel/03'    '/channel/04'    '/channel/05'

  Columns 7 through 12

    '/channel/06'    '/channel/07'    '/channel/08'    '/channel/09'    '/channel/10'    '/channel/11'

  Columns 13 through 18

    '/channel/12'    '/channel/13'    '/channel/14'    '/channel/15'    '/channel/16'    '/channel/17'

  Columns 19 through 24

The group attributes tersely tell us this channel contains atmospheric pressure data from a resonant pressure transducer from a tower location at 20 meters height. We see that this group contains some datasets. Each contains 289296 data points. All data points in each dataset have the same type. These datasets of channel 24 contain 2 or 4-byte floating point numbers. Further information displayed by h5disp falls outside of the scope of this tutorial.

We have not used the h5disp function before, because it outputs too much information. Although when passing 'min' as a third argument, the verbosity is greatly reduced—see the section ‘Appendix: Full Hierarchy Tree’ at the end of this tutorial.

Datasets can also have attributes, but that is not being used in the OWEZ HDF5 file we are using here. One use case for that would be to store data that is removed for some reason from the dataset. In our file, this has been done at the group (channel) level. We first look at which channels have which attributes and then have a look at an ‘interesting’ one:

>> ciGA = {channel_info.Groups.Attributes};
>> c = containers.Map;

>> for i = 1:length(ciGA),
     ks = {ciGA{i}.Name};
     for j = 1:length(ks),
       if isKey(c, ks{j}),
         c(ks{j}) = [c(ks{j}), i];
       else,
         c(ks{j}) = [i];
       end,
     end,
   end

Exploring the Hierarchy

Now that we know what groups and datasets are, we can explore the structure of the HDF5 file a bit more, to learn how it can be used to store the datasets in a self-describing way.

As a reminder, let us recall the highest level of the file:

>> {info.Groups.Name}

ans =

  1×4 cell array

    '/channel'    '/coordinates'    '/device'    '/time'

We have looked at the 'channel' group, which structured the datasets according to the scheme used in the original Excel data files.

Device–Quantity–Location Hierarchy

The datasets are also available in an alternative structure from the channel one. Namely, they can be accessed through the device–quantity–location hierarchy:

    'This group contains a device/quantity/location ordering of the datasets…'

     Datatypes: []
         Links: []
    Attributes: [1×1 struct]

So we see that in this alternative hierarchy, the datasets can be reached by specifying the device, quantity, and location, in that order. At that point, we find again the same datasets we encountered in the flat channel hierarchy. These have been grafted here using so-called ‘soft’ links (this does not matter much in practice).

What is especially convenient about such a more descriptive hierarchy is that at the right level metadata of interest can be added. For example references to device make and type:

>> disp({info_WM.Attributes.Name})
    'owez_code'    'make'    'type'    'description'

>> disp(h5readatt('OWEZ.h5', '/device/WM', 'make')),...
   disp(h5readatt('OWEZ.h5', '/device/WM', 'type'))
    'Gill'

    'Windmaster 1086M'

Given that it is natural that each quantity is treated in the same way, information about the data processing is stored at that level:

>> disp(h5readatt('OWEZ.h5', '/device/WM/vws', 'sampling_frequency')),...
   disp(h5readatt('OWEZ.h5', '/device/WM/vws', 'standard_error')),...
   disp(h5readatt('OWEZ.h5', '/device/WM/vws', 'storage'))
    '4 Hz (2400 samples per 10 min)'

    'Given that √2400 is about 50, the standard error of the Mean, i.e., due…'

    'The Max and Min fields have been stored as float16 values. This results…'

Toying with Datasets Again

Plotting against the timestamps is straightforward:

>> vws116Mean = h5read('OWEZ.h5', '/device/WM/vws/NW116/Mean');
>> vws116Min = h5read('OWEZ.h5', '/device/WM/vws/NW116/Min');
>> vws116Max = h5read('OWEZ.h5', '/device/WM/vws/NW116/Max');
>> vws116StdDev = h5read('OWEZ.h5', '/device/WM/vws/NW116/StdDev');

>> h = figure(); hold on;
>> plot(t, vws116Mean + vws116StdDev, 'g'), plot(t, vws116Mean - vws116StdDev, 'g'),...
plot(t, vws116Min, 'r'), plot(t, vws116Max, 'r'), plot(t, vws116Mean, 'b');

The mean vertical wind speed is usually small, a slight updraft, but with substantially larger extrema over the ten-minute averaging windows.

Zooming in on a specific part—e.g., the winter of 2007–2008—of the dataset is simplified by using the year and month indexes we encountered earlier:

>> s = ((y == 2007) & (m == 12)) | ((y == 2008) & (m == 1));
>> h = figure(); hold on;
>> plot(t(s), vws116Mean(s) + vws116StdDev(s), 'g'),...
   plot(t(s), vws116Mean(s) - vws116StdDev(s), 'g'),...
   plot(t(s), vws116Min(s), 'r'), plot(t(s), vws116Max(s), 'r'),...
   plot(t(s), vws116Mean(s), 'b');

There seems to be some extreme negative (downward) value in the third week of december; let's find out how extreme and where precisely.

>> [vws116Mean_min, i] = nanmin(vws116Mean(s))

vws116Mean_min =

  single

   -5.2800


i =

        2934

>> ts = t(s); ts(i)

ans =

  int32

   1198223400

>> datestr(datetime(ts(i), 'ConvertFrom', 'posixtime'))

ans =

21-Dec-2007 07:50:00

>> a = h5read('OWEZ.h5', '/time/day');
>> s = (y == 2007) & (m == 12) & (a == 21);
>> [vws116Mean_min, i] = nanmin(vws116Mean(s));
>> ts = t(s); tsc = double(ts - ts(i))/60/60; % we center the plot at the extreme value
>> h = figure(); hold on;
>> plot(tsc, vws116Mean(s) + vws116StdDev(s), 'g'),...
   plot(tsc, vws116Mean(s) - vws116StdDev(s), 'g'),...
   plot(tsc, vws116Min(s), 'r'), plot(tsc, vws116Max(s), 'r'),...
   plot(tsc, vws116Mean(s), 'b');

Well, that doesn't seem like a good measurement day. Perhaps those data should be cut out because doubts about their reliability.

Closing

If you managed to work through all of the above examples, you should be ready to independently work with HDF5 files yourself using Matlab. Remember that the hierarchy of each HDF5 file can be different, so it will be necessary to acquaint yourself with it a bit before working with the data.

In case you are dealing with a HDF5 file that you want to augment or improve, or if you want to create an HDF5 file for some dataset, I advise you to go over the Matlab documentation. I haven't used Matlab in the creation and modification of HDF5 files yet, mostly because I have a personal preference for Python. However, don't hesitate to contact me to share experiences.

Success & have fun!
